column5: ORALFORE-1972
Opposed Rates of Advance of Large Forces in Europe (ORALFORE)
Historical Evaluation and Research Organization
Prepared for US Army Deputy Chief of Staff for Operations (DAMO-PLW)
2301 Gallows Road
Dunn Loring, VA 22027
28 August 1972
U
DTIC as AD-902 830
Dr. Robert L. Helmbold, US Army Concepts Analysis Agency
Spreadsheet last revised:
P = Pause, Y = Yes, U = Unknown, NA = Not applicable, NU = Not used,
NR = Not recorded in the ORALFORE report
WEATHER ARMOR = Judgment of suitability of weather for armor operations
WEATHER AIR = Judgment of suitability of weather for air operations
TERRAIN = Judgment of terrain mobility
ROADNET = Judgment of roadnet suitability for mobility
OBSTACLES = Obstacles to advance, coded as follows.
DM = Exceptionally effective demolitions, DS = Desert, FL = Flooded area,
FZ= Fortified zone, R = River, SA = Sabotage by local populace, UR = Urban
area
OPP'N INT'Y = Intensity of opposition to advance, coded as follows.
I = Intense, M = Moderate, S = Slight, N = Negligible
ATK COND'N = Attacker's readiness condition, coded as follows.
FR = Fresh, T = Tired, W = Weary, E = Exhausted
ATK MISS'N = Attacker's posture/mission, coded as follows. (Mixed entries
in ORALFORE coded as fractions. I.e., ORALFORE entry 2-3 coded as 2.5.)
1 = Unlimited, 2 = Related to specific objectives or contingencies,
3 = Related to adjacent unit's advance, 4 = Limited by higher
authority control, 5 = Other
ATK CAS% = Attacker's losses in percent.
DEF COND'N = Defender's readiness conditin, coded as follows.
FR = Fresh, T = Tired, W = Weary, E = Exhausted
DEF MISS'N = Defender's posture/mission, coded as follows.
WD = Withdrawal, HD = Hasty defense, FD = Fortified defense,
PD = Position defense, DL = Delay
DEF CAS% = Defender's casualties in percent
